In this article, President Biden addresses the Glasgow Climate Summit and emphasizes the need to raise ambitions in order to limit global warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius. He highlights the importance of setting concrete plans to decarbonize economies and achieve net-zero emissions by 2050. President Biden emphasizes the immediate scaling up of clean technologies such as wind and solar energy, citing the United States' goal of deploying 30 gigawatts of offshore wind by 2030. He also emphasizes the need for innovation in developing and commercializing new clean energy technologies by 2030. President Biden mentions clean hydrogen, long-duration energy storage, next-generation renewables, nuclear energy, carbon capture, and sustainable agriculture as areas for investment and breakthroughs. He announces the launch of the First Movers Coalition, a partnership between the United States and the World Economic Forum, which aims to push for commercially viable alternatives to decarbonize industrial sectors. President Biden also highlights the role of the agricultural sector in the climate fight and announces the launch of the Agriculture Innovation Mission for Climate (AIM for Climate) in collaboration with the United Arab Emirates. AIM for Climate aims to catalyze public and private investment in climate-smart agriculture and food system innovation, with an initial investment of $4 billion globally, of which the United States plans to mobilize $1 billion over the next five years. President Biden concludes by emphasizing the need for collective action and the United States' commitment to lead by example and share its powers of innovation with the world.